rugs.com/pregnancy/protamine.html|website=www.drugs.com|accessdate=14 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221010812/https://www.drugs.com/pregnancy/protamine.html|archivedate=21 December 2016}}</ref> Protamine works by binding with [[heparin]].<ref name=AHFS2016/>\n\n<!-- History and culture -->\nProtamine sulfate was approved for medical use in the United States in 1969.<ref name=AHFS2016/> It is on the [[WHO Model List of Essential Medicines|World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines]], the safest and most effective medicines needed in a [[health system]].<ref name=\"WHO21st\">{{cite book | vauthors = ((World Health Organization)) | title = World Health Organization model list of essential medicines: 21st list 2019 | year = 2019 | hdl = 10665/325771 | author-link = World Health Organization | publisher = World Health Organization | location = Geneva | id = WHO/MVP/EMP/IAU/2019.06. License: CC BY-NC-SA 3.0 IGO | hdl-access=free }}</ref> The wholesale cost in the [[developing world]] is about US$2.82\u201312.20 per vial.<ref name=ERC2014>{{cite web|title=Protamine Sulfate|url=http://mshpriceguide.org/en/single-drug-information/?DMFId=676&searchYear=2014|website=International Drug Price Indicator Guide|accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref> It was originally made from the sperm of [[salmon]].<ref name=AHFS2016>{{cite web|title=Protamine Sulfate|url=https://www.drugs.com/monograph/protamine-sulfate.html|publisher=The American Society of Health-System Pharmacists|accessdate=8 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106063702/https://www.drugs.com/monograph/protamine-sulfate.html|archivedate=6 November 2016}}</ref> It is now mainly made using [[recombinant biotechnology]].<ref name=Kern2012>{{cite book |last1=Kern |first1=Morton J. |title=The Interventional Cardiac Catheterization Handbook E-Book |date=2012 |publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences |isbn=9781455740420 |page=131 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=E27-2_qutX0C&pg=PA131 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Medical uses==\nProtamine sulfate is usually administered to reverse the large dose of heparin administered during certain surgeries, especially heart surgery where anti-coagulation is necessary to prevent clot formation within the cardiopulmonary bypass pump apparatus. A dose of protamine is given once the patient is off-pump, when extracorporeal circulation and anticoagulation are no longer needed.\n\nIt is also used in gene transfer, protein purification and in tissue cultures as a [[crosslinker]] for viral transduction. In gene therapy, protamine sulfate has been studied as a means to increase transduction rates by both viral and nonviral-mediated delivery mechanisms (e.g. utilizing [[cationic liposome]]s).<ref name=\"Sorgi 1997\">{{cite journal|last=Sorgi|first=FL|author2=Bhattacharya, S|author3=Huang, L|title=Protamine sulfate enhances lipid-mediated gene transfer.|journal=Gene Therapy|date=Sep 1997|volume=4|issue=9|pages=961\u20138|doi=10.1038/sj.gt.3300484|pmid=9349433|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"Cornetta 1989\">{{cite journal | author= Kenneth Cornetta | author2 = W.French Anderson | title = Protamine sulfate as an effective alternative to polybrene in retroviral-mediated gene-transfer: implications for human gene therapy | journal = Journal of Virological Methods | year= 1989 | volume= 23 | issue= 2 | pages= 187\u2013194 | doi=10.1016/0166-0934(89)90132-8 | pmid= 2786000}}</ref>\n\nProtamine is used in [[insulin aspart protamine]] and [[NPH insulin]].\n\n===Dosage===\nDosage for heparin reversal is 1.0 to 1.5&nbsp;mg protamine sulfate IV for every 100 IU of active heparin. [[Partial thromboplastin time|PTT]] should be monitored at 5 to 15 minutes after dose then in 2\u20138 hours afterward.\n\n==Adverse effects==\nProtamine has been reported to cause [[allergic reactions]] in patients who are allergic to fish, diabetics using [[insulin]] preparations containing protamine, and vasectomized or infertile men.<ref name=\"Walker 1984\">{{cite journal|last=Walker|first=WS|author2=Reid, KG|author3=Hider, CF|author4=Davidson, IA|author5=Boulton, FE. |title=Successful cardiopulmonary bypass in diabetics with anaphylactoid reactions to protamine.|journal=Br Heart J|date=1984|volume=52|issue=1|pages=112\u2013114|doi=10.1136/hrt.52.1.112|pmid=6743419|pmc=481594}}</ref><ref name=\"Campbell 1984\">{{cite journal|last=Campbell|first=FW|author2=Goldstein, MF|author3=Atkins, PC. |title=Management of the patient with protamine hypersensitivity for cardiac surgery.|journal=Anesthesiology|date=1984|volume=61|issue=6|pages=761\u2013764|doi=10.1097/00000542-198412000-00021|pmid=6334459}}</ref> These occur at rates ranging from 0.28% to 6%.<ref name=\"Campbell 1984\" /><ref name=\"Welsby 2005\">{{cite journal|last=Welsby|first=IJ|author2=Newman, MF|author3=Phillips-Bute, B|author4=Messier, RH|author5=Kakkis, ED. |title=Hemodynamic changes after protamine administration: association with mortality after coronary artery bypass surgery.|journal=Anesthesiology |date=2005|volume=102|issue=2|pages=308\u2013314 |doi=10.1097/00000542-200502000-00011|pmid=15681944}}</ref><ref name=\"Sokolowska 2016\">{{cite journal|last=Sokolowska|first=E|author2=Kalaska, B|author3=Miklosz, J|author4=Mogielnicki, A.|title=The toxicology of heparin reversal with protamine: past, present and future.|journal=Expert Opinion on Drug Metabolism & Toxicology|date=2016|volume=6|issue=8|pages=897\u2013909|doi=10.1080/17425255.2016.1194395|pmid=27223896}}</ref>\n\nAvoiding rapid [[Route of administration|infusion]] of protamine sulfate and pre-treating at-risk patients with [[histamine receptor antagonist]]s (H1 and H2) and [[steroids]] may minimize these reactions. A 5 to 10&nbsp;mg test dose is recommended following pretreatment before administering the full dose.<ref name=\"Campbell 1984\" />\n\n==Mechanism==\nIt is a highly [[cationic]] peptide that binds to either heparin or [[low molecular weight heparin]] (LMWH) to form a stable ion pair, which does not have anticoagulant activity. The ionic complex is then removed and broken down by the [[reticuloendothelial system]]. In large doses, protamine sulfate may also have an independent \u2014 however weak \u2014 anticoagulant effect.\n\n==History==\n[[Protamine]] was originally isolated from the sperm of salmon, but is now mostly made by [[Recombinant DNA|recombinant]] biotechnology.<ref name= Recombinant2019 /><ref name=Kern2012/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MeshName|Protamine+Sulfate}}\n\n{{Antihemorrhagics}}\n{{Antidotes}}\n\n[[Category:Antidotes]]\n[[Category:World Health Organization essential medicines]]\n[[Category:RTT]]\n\n{{portal bar|Pharmacy and pharmacology|Medicine}}\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "added FDA UNII to drug box", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protamine_sulfate"}
